{"id":14881854,"mediaExerciseId":"d4cc284f-276e-40f9-a7ba-b6d1ee2cbdf2","exerciseName":"4","chapterName":"24","chapterTitle":"Options and Corporate Finance","groupId":null,"groupTitle":null,"isPremium":true,"sectionName":"24.4","sectionTitle":"Employee Stock Options","pageNumber":807,"solutions":[{"id":5996666,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this problem, we must determine the key differences between a traded stock option and an ESO.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"**Employee stock option or ESO** is a type of equity compensation companies grant to their employees and executives. The company gives derivative options on the stock rather than granting shares of stock.\n","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"**Traded stock options** is the trading of instruments that gives the holder the right to buy or sell a security on a specific date at a specific price.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":66,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/08/7f38fb6dbdd1f3c6645b00d942657bac/abef12dfcead00034a28a39666071ac5/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":34,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/08/7f38fb6dbdd1f3c6645b00d942657bac/abef12dfcead00034a28a39666071ac5/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"The key differences between a traded stock option and employee stock options (ESO) are that ESOs have a longer life than traded stock options, and ESOs cannot be sold and cannot be exercised during the vesting period. When an employee leaves the company, ESOs are lost, but traded stock options are not.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":105,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/08/7f38fb6dbdd1f3c6645b00d942657bac/217c90d56aa05719e2e64f5b94ddacb3/lateximg_large.png","width":1017},"regular":{"height":53,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/08/7f38fb6dbdd1f3c6645b00d942657bac/217c90d56aa05719e2e64f5b94ddacb3/lateximg.png","width":509}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4},{"columns":[{"text":"**ESO repricing** occurs when an issuing firm resets the strike price of an ESO, most frequently after a significant decline in the stock price. ESO repricing is controversial due to its backdating. This means that ESO was granted earlier than it really was to improve the value of the option.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":68,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/08/7f38fb6dbdd1f3c6645b00d942657bac/776c683b3fdf89f3ce4e5cd06fbac007/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":34,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/08/7f38fb6dbdd1f3c6645b00d942657bac/776c683b3fdf89f3ce4e5cd06fbac007/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":5}],"rating":5,"solutionUuid":"168e642f-8cad-44c8-a8c1-9fb460f7ed4d","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":5}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of Corporate Finance","edition":"12th Edition","verifiedSolutionCount":1217,"shouldBeIndexableForSeo":true,"modified":1665448474394,"active":true,"publisher":"McGraw-Hill Education","mainTextbookIsbn":null,"subjects":{"level1":["Social Science"],"level2":["Economics"],"level3":["Finance"]}},"nextExercises":[{"id":14881855,"